<b>Probability Distributions</b>

<body>

<p>This document will aim to assure you understand different probability distributions, and there following use cases. In class, we discussed discrete and continuous distributions.  Consider the following situations and suggest a probability distribution that would be suitable to model each situation.  Note that just a slight change in modeling a situation can change the distribution. For each situation below, consider what <b>distribution</b> you would use, what <b>each parameter would represent</b>, and what the random variable <b>X</b> would represent in each case.</p>
<br></br>
<ol>
  <li>Consider we are interested in modeling the number of people we see in the area who wear tie. </li>
  <ul>
      <li> Distribution: <b>Poisson</b>
      <br></br>
      <br></br>
      <li> Parameters: <b>Lambda is the only parameter for the Poisson distribution, which is equal to the mean and the variance.</b>
      <br></br>
      <br></br>
      <li> Random Variable: <b>The random variable (X) is the number of people we see wearing ties.  Likely measured daily.  The count would be a new count of the number of individuals wearing a tie, collected for each day.</b>
      <br></br>
      <br></br>
  </ul>
  <br></br>
  <li>What if (twisting the above situation) we just looked at the number of people wearing a tie out of the first 100 people that we saw?</li>
    <ul>
      <li> Distribution: <b>Binomial Distribution</b>
      <br></br>
      <br></br>
      <li> Parameters: <b> n = 100, p = proportion of individuals wearing a tie out of the 100 people.</b>
      <br></br>
      <br></br>
      <li> Random Variable: <b>The count of the number of individuals wearing a tie.</b>
      <br></br>
      <br></br>
  </ul>
  <li>What if we wanted to model the number of individuals until we saw our *first* person wearing a tie?  
    <ul>
      <li> Distribution: <b>Geometric Distribution</b>
      <br></br>
      <br></br>
      <li> Parameters: <b>p = the probability of any one person wearing a tie.</b>
      <br></br>
      <br></br>
      <li> Random Variable:<b>The number of 'non-tie wearers' until you see your first 'tie wearer'.</b>
      <br></br>
      <br></br>
  </ul>
    <li> Consider for all of the above situations, the probability of a male individual wearing a tie on a weekday is 35%.  On Saturday, the probability of a male wearing a tie on a Saturday is 1%.  On Sunday, the probability of a male wearing a tie is 15%.  Additionally, assume that the proportion of males to females is 53% to 47%, respectively.  For the purposes of this problem, consider the probability of a female wearing a tie on any given day is the same at .5%.  Additionally assume there are 450,000 people that live in the area.  
    <br></br>
    <ul>
        <li> Based on the above scenario, determine the probability that any individual is wearing a tie.
<br></br>
