<br></br>
<p>There is also a 0.53 chance that an individual is male, and a 0.47 chance that an individual is female.  Additionally, with no day provided, there is a 5/7 chance that a day is a weekday and 1/7 for the probability of Saturday and Sunday.  Multiplying to acheive the probability of a tie for each possible scenario: male, weekday, tie; male, Sunday, tie; male, Saturday, tie; male, Sunday, tie; or female, tie. We can calculate each of these probabilities as shown below:</p>

<!--begin.rcode
mwt = .53*(5/7)*.35
msat = .53*(1/7)*.01
msut = .53*(1/7)*.15
ft = .47*.005
end.rcode-->

This provides the following total probability of wearing a tie:

<!--begin.rcode
mwt + msat + msut + ft
end.rcode-->

        <li> Calculate the probability of an individual being a male given that they are are not wearing a tie.
<br></br>
<p>Notice, the probability of an individual being male given that they are not wearing a tie is equal to the probability of being male and not wearing a tie divided by the probability of not wearing a tie.  We can find the probability of not wearing a tie similarly to the way we found the probability of wearing a tie, which gives:</b>

<!--begin.rcode
mwn = .53*(5/7)*.65
msan = .53*(1/7)*.99
msun = .53*(1/7)*.85
fn = .47*.995
mwn + msan + msun + fn
end.rcode-->

<p>Then the probability of being male and not wearing a tie is just the first three equations above.  This gives us the probability of male given that you are not wearing a tie as:</p>

<!--begin.rcode
(mwn + msan + msun)/(mwn + msan + msun + fn)
end.rcode-->

        <li> Now, calculate the expected number of individuals in the community that are wearing ties for each day.
            <br></br>
<p>Using the above probabilities, we can determine the probability of a tie for each day.  We need to condition on the day we are on.  So we are finding the probability of tie given a particular day.  </p>
<ul>
  <li> Weekday:
<!--begin.rcode
(mwt)/(5/7) + ft
end.rcode-->
  <li> Saturday:
<!--begin.rcode
(msat)/(1/7) + ft
end.rcode-->  
  <li> Sunday:
<!--begin.rcode
(msut)/(1/7) + ft
end.rcode-->
</ul>

<p>Then, using the above probabilities, the expected values for each case are:</p>
<ul>
  <li> Weekday:
<!--begin.rcode
((mwt)/(5/7) + ft)*450000
end.rcode-->
  <li> Saturday:
<!--begin.rcode
((msat)/(1/7) + ft)*450000
end.rcode-->  
  <li> Sunday:
<!--begin.rcode
((msut)/(1/7) + ft)*450000
end.rcode-->
</ul>
<br></br>
        <li> Calculate the probability of seeing no one wearing a tie for each day.  What are your assumptions when calculating this probability?
        <bt></br>
<p>Since we are calculating this for each day, we can assume we are given which day we are in.  Therefore, this probability can be canceled out.</p>        
<ul>
  <li> Weekday:
<!--begin.rcode
(mwn/(5/7) + fn)
end.rcode-->
  <li> Saturday:
<!--begin.rcode
(msan/(1/7) + fn)
end.rcode-->  
  <li> Sunday:
<!--begin.rcode
(msun/(1/7) + fn)
end.rcode-->
</ul>
<br></br>
<p>We are assuming that each individual that we see is independent of every other individual.  We are assuming that no weekday is any different than any other weekday, similarly idea with Saturday and Sunday.  If more people are more likely to wear ties on Easter Sunday than other Sundays our modeling approach does not account for this fact.</p>

<p>Then we are interested in finding the probability of no one wearing a tie on a particular day.  We can find this probability by using a Binomial distribution with n = 450000 and p of the probability shown for a particular day.</p>
<br></br>
  <li> Weekday:
<!--begin.rcode
dbinom(0, 450000, (1-(mwn/(5/7) + fn)))
end.rcode-->
  <li> Saturday:
<!--begin.rcode
dbinom(0, 450000, (1-(msan/(1/7) + fn)))
end.rcode-->  
  <li> Sunday:
<!--begin.rcode
dbinom(0, 450000, (1-(msun/(1/7) + fn)))
end.rcode-->
</ul>
<br></br>

        <li>  If we don't know what day it is, what is the minimum probability of seeing at least 1 person with a tie? What is the maximum probability of seeing at least 1 person with a tie?
        <br></br>
<p>Similar to the above, we could calculate the probability of one more people wearing a tie as:</p>
  <li> Weekday:
<!--begin.rcode
1-dbinom(0, 450000, (1-(mwn/(5/7) + fn)))
end.rcode-->
  <li> Saturday:
<!--begin.rcode
1-dbinom(0, 450000, (1-(msan/(1/7) + fn)))
end.rcode-->  
  <li> Sunday:
<!--begin.rcode
1-dbinom(0, 450000, (1-(msun/(1/7) + fn)))
end.rcode-->
</ul>
<br></br>
<p>It is now trivial to answer both questions posed.  Nevermind...didn't expect for both of those to be 1.  It clearly doesn't matter what day it is.  You expect someone will be wearing a tie somewhere in your town with probability 1.</p>
<br></br>
    

        <li> Considering it is a Sunday, how many people do you expect to see before you see your first person wearing a tie?
        <br></br>
<p>Here, we are working with a Geometric distribution with p as given for Sunday above.  Therefore, we have the expected value as 1/p or </p>

<!--begin.rcode
1/(1-(msun/(1/7) + fn))
end.rcode-->


<br></br>
        <li> If we look at 100 individuals from the community (assume random), what is the probability 15 of these individuals are wearing ties on a Tuesday?
        <br></br>
<p>Again here, we are using the Binomial distribution.  Since, Tuesday is a weekday, we will use the probability associated with a weekday to find this probability.  This can be done in the following way:</p>

<!--begin.rcode
dbinom(15, 100, (1-(mwn/(5/7) + fn)))
end.rcode-->

        <br></br>
        <li> Consider we additionally know that if someone has a tie, they have a 40% chance of stopping at our shop.  However, if they do not have a tie, they have a 5% chance of stopping at our shop.  Assuming every person in the community has a 15% chance of passing by our shop, what is the expected number of people that will stop into our shop?
        <br></br>
 <p>Since the total probability of wearing a tie is as shown above (about 15%), we know that 15% of these individuals have a chance of passing by our shop.  Similarly, approximately 85% of individuals are not wearing a tie and 15% of these individuals have a chance of passing by our shop.  We can find the chance that an individual wearing a tie stops at our shop as approximately:</p>
<br></br>
<!--begin.rcode
.15*.15*.4
end.rcode-->
<br></br>
<p>Alternatively, we can find the probability that an individual not wearing a tie stops by our shop as approximately:</p>
<br></br>
<!--begin.rcode
.85*.15*.05
end.rcode-->
<p>Therefore, the total probability is given by the sum, and the expected value is this probability times the number of individuals in the community.</p>
<br></br>
<!--begin.rcode
((.15*.15*.4)+(.85*.15*.05))*450000
end.rcode-->

<p>With no idea about which day it might be, we might expect this number of individuals to stop by our store (given all the the probabilities defined are accurate, and non-varying).</p> 
